R and RStudio


R Project is a free software environment for statistical computing and graphics.
R is available for download for Linux, Windows and Mac OS X.
Tutorial Quick-R


Rstudio is the premier integrated development environment (IDE) for R.
Rstudio is available for download for Linux, Windows and Mac OS X, and it requires R is previously installed.

See overview video about RStudio

Basic commands:

Install and load library:

install.packages("phyloseq")
library(phyloseq)

Load and run an R script:

When you have an already written R script:

source('scriptR.r')

Working directory:

wd: working directory

getwd() # Find current directory, where input/output files are located by default
setwd('ProgrammingChallenges/PracticeR') # Change the current working directory

Help:

?write.table

Basic data types:

  • numeric
varNum <- 4
class(varNum)
## [1] "numeric"
typeof(varNum) # low-level type ('double' or 'complex' (1+3i))
## [1] "double"
  • character
varChar <- 'myVariable'
class(varChar)
## [1] "character"
  • logical
varBool <- TRUE
class(varBool)
## [1] "logical"

Conversion between types

Function Description
as.character(var) Convert variable var to character vector
as.numeric(var) Convert variable var to numeric type
as.integer(var) Convert variable var to integer type
as.logical(var) Convert variable var to TRUE or FALSE
as.matrix(var) Convert variable var (i.e. data.frame) to matrix

Examples:

x <- 5.3
y1 <- as.character(x)
y2 <- as.logical(x)
y3 <- as.integer(x)
x
## [1] 5.3
y1
## [1] "5.3"
y2
## [1] TRUE
y3
## [1] 5

Data structures:

  • vector

    vector creation:
c(3, 7.5, 2.2) # concat elements
## [1] 3.0 7.5 2.2
c("on", "of", "from") # character vector
## [1] "on"   "of"   "from"
c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE) # logical vector
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
15:23
## [1] 15 16 17 18 19 20 21 22 23
rep(5, times=3) # repeat a element/vector
## [1] 5 5 5
rep(1:2, each=3) # repeat elements of a vector
## [1] 1 1 1 2 2 2
seq(from=2, to=5, by=0.5) # sequence
## [1] 2.0 2.5 3.0 3.5 4.0 4.5 5.0
vector element access by position [index]
v <- c(3, 5, 10, 15, 18, 25)
v[2]
## [1] 5
v[1:3]
## [1]  3  5 10
v[c(2,4,6)] # Indices generated from other vector
## [1]  5 15 25
vector element access by value (comparisons)
v <- c(3, 5, 10, 15, 18, 25)
v[v == 10]
## [1] 10
v[v < 15]
## [1]  3  5 10
v[v %in% c(1,3,5)]
## [1] 3 5
vector operations: All elements at once:
v1 <- c(10,12,15,20)
v1
## [1] 10 12 15 20
v2 <- 1:4
v2
## [1] 1 2 3 4
3 * v1  # A (scalar) number with all vector elements
## [1] 30 36 45 60
v1 + v2 # One by one element operations between two equal-length vectors
## [1] 11 14 18 24

  • string:

    String is a character vector. There are specific functions defined to make easy the string management.

Concatenate several strings (x, y)

paste(x, y, sep = '')

Number of characters in the string

nchar(x)

Retrive part of the string, limited by ini and end

substring(x, ini, end)

Find regular expresion (pattern) matches in string x

grep(pattern, x)

Replace matches of regular expresion (pattern) in string x with a new string (replace)

gsub(pattern, replace, x)

Convert to uppercase/lowercase

toupper(x)
tolower(x)

Examples:

paste('Hello',"word")
## [1] "Hello word"
sequence='ACTGCGTCCGATTAGTACTTAtGTCGATCGATCGATCAGTCCAGTCA'
substring(sequence,15,nchar(sequence))
## [1] "GTACTTAtGTCGATCGATCGATCAGTCCAGTCA"
grep('UA',sequence)
## integer(0)
grep('AT',sequence)
## [1] 1
gsub('AT','--',sequence)
## [1] "ACTGCGTCCG--TAGTACTTAtGTCG--CG--CG--CAGTCCAGTCA"
tolower(sequence)
## [1] "actgcgtccgattagtacttatgtcgatcgatcgatcagtccagtca"

More string functions in stringr library.

  • matrix

    Data structures as vector although with 2 or more dimensions. Matrix creation:
m <- matrix(data = NA, nrow = 1, ncol = 1, byrow = FALSE)

Access matrix element, by indeces:

m[indexRow,indexColumn]

Examples:

# Creation
matrix(1:6, 2, 3)
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    3    5
## [2,]    2    4    6
m<-matrix(1:9, 3, 3, byrow = T)
m
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    2    3
## [2,]    4    5    6
## [3,]    7    8    9
# Dimensions
dim(m)
## [1] 3 3
# Access
m[2,3]
## [1] 6
m[2:3,c(1,3)]
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    4    6
## [2,]    7    9
# Operation
m+10
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]   11   12   13
## [2,]   14   15   16
## [3,]   17   18   19

  • factor

    Similar to character vector, but with values restricted to specific levels (categories). Internally, it is represented as integers. Each level has associated a representative string. Useful to count or for statistical purposes.
varFac <- factor(c('apple','orange','grapes','orange','apple','apple'))
varFac
## [1] apple  orange grapes orange apple  apple 
## Levels: apple grapes orange
class(varFac)
## [1] "factor"
levels(varFac)
## [1] "apple"  "grapes" "orange"
varFac=="orange"
## [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
table(varFac)
## varFac
##  apple grapes orange 
##      3      1      2

  • data.frame

    Most common R data structures to store tables. It contains several vectors of the same length, but whatever type. Each column or/and row could have a name/header. It could be consider a special type of list, where the different objects are the same length (although different types)

Creation:

dfEcoliGenes <- data.frame(item=1:4,
            id=as.factor(c('JW4367', 'JW0001', 'JW0002', 'JW0003')),
            name=c('thrL','thrA','thrB','thrC'),
            length=c(21,820,310,428))
dfEcoliGenes
##   item     id name length
## 1    1 JW4367 thrL     21
## 2    2 JW0001 thrA    820
## 3    3 JW0002 thrB    310
## 4    4 JW0003 thrC    428

Data frames are usually read from big tables in text (comma or tab separated) files:

df=read.table('tableEnsembl.tsv',sep="\t",header=TRUE,quote="",stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Useful data frame functions:

Function Description
str(df) Check type structure
head(df) Check first df rows. Check the content was right loaded.
tail(df) Check last df rows
colnames(df) Vector with column names
rownames(df) Vector with row names
nrow(df), ncol(df), dim(df) Row or column number (or both)

head/tail are very useful in big data frames.

or several conditions to filter the rows (for example, chromosome 22 AND (&) removing sequences shorther than 2000):

dfx = subset(dfi, chr=='22' & length>2000)
nrow(dfx)
## [1] 764

For an alternative condition, to use OR (|)

  • data.table

    data.table is a data structure to enhance the R standard structure, it is, the data.frame.

The syntaxis of this new data structure compared with could be explored in the vignette of the data.table library

Note: In general, both data structures (tibble with dplyr and data.table) are suitable to manage big tables. However, when you table is huge (~millions of rows), data.table is the fastest, although tibble with dplyr provides more kind syntaxis. (Sources comparison dplyr and data.table packages: https://freakonometrics.hypotheses.org/19645, https://dlegorreta.wordpress.com/r-vs-r-realmente-es-dplyr-vs-data-table/)

* Note: Additionally, you could design your self user-defined data class. Some examples of this advanced use below (i.e. mart, phyloseq class)

Read/Write tables in a file (data.frame)

df=read.table('tableEnsembl.tsv',sep="\t",header=TRUE,quote="",stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

write.table(df,file='tableEnsembl.tsv',quote=FALSE,sep="\t",row.names=FALSE)

sep parameter represents the field separator character

  • sep=“,” if columns split by ‘,’
  • sep=“\t” if columns split by tab

Check the data structure/class/type:

typeof(), class()

v <- c(3, 5, 10, 15, 18, 25)
typeof(v)
## [1] "double"
typeof(v)
## [1] "double"
c <- "Checking data type"
class(c)
## [1] "character"

  • Inf (Infinite)

Function definition

To modulate and organize the code in independent blocks.

# Function definition
functionName <- function(param1, param2=defaultValueParam2,...)
{
  <instructions>
  ...
  return(result)
}
# Call to the function
a=functionName(34,'ABCD')

Bioconductor

How to install packages designed for bioinformatics operations with biological data.

source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite() # Install basic bioinformatics packages
biocLite('biomaRt') # Install additional ones

One of the useful packages in Bioconductor is biomaRt, allowing access to Ensembl repository through programmatic access with R:

library(biomaRt)

First, you need to define a mart object with the specific dataset. For example, to use human ensembl one:

ensembl <- useMart("ensembl", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")

Then, the main retrievement function of the biomaRt package is getBM()

resEnsembl <- getBM(attributes =  myAttributes, filters =  myFilter,
             values =  myValues, mart = ensembl)

where, you must define:
* the attributes you want to retrieve as output properties of each register (i.e. gene/protein). They must be included in the available list.
* the filters to apply as input in the query. Also, they must be selected from the provided list.
* the vector of values of the filter. If there are several filters, several vectors are expected, in the same order than in the filters argument.
* the mart object (biomart dataset) where do the search, previously defined with useMart()

For example, the query to find all genes within chromosomes 20 and 22, described by their start and end position, % GC and gene textual description, would be:

# A) Define arguments:
# Define attributes

phyloseq: microbiome data manipulation

phyloseq is an R package included in Bioconductor to work with microbiome data.
website
McMurdie and Holmes, 2013

phyloseq defines its self data structure, composed by:

  • OTU table: matrix with OTU abundances in each cell, with samples in columns and OTUs in rows.
  • taxonomy: matrix with up to seven levels of the taxonomic classification associated to each OTU. Taxonomic levels in columns and OTUs in rows. If some level is unknown in a sample, it could be labeled as NA.
  • sampling: list of different vectors, with one vector per attribute or property describing each microbiome sample.
  • (Optionally: phylogenetic tree and sequences)

phyloseq provides multiple functions to access, filter or visualize microbiome data loaded in its phyloseq format.

Input data

To create a phyloseq object you always require (other elements are optional):

  • OTU table
  • sample data

There are two main options to import the data to get a phyloseq object:

  • file in standard biom format (http://biom-format.org/) (i.e. OTU table). You additionally could add phylogenetic tree and sequences are additional parameters in import_biom(). The sampling data should be imported independently, depending on its format (.csv, qiime, etc).
biom.otu<-import_biom(biomFile)
map<-import_qiime_sample_data(mapBiomFile)
data <- merge_phyloseq(biom.otu,map)

There are similar functions for OTU input file in other format (qiime, mothur, etc.)

  • OTU table and mapping in csv/tsv format. In this case, you first read the table as a data.frame (read.table()), and after you convert it to a otu_table in the phyloseq required format (otu_table()). The same procedure should be follow for the mapping file (using read.table() and sample_data() in this case). Finally, to join both objects in a phyloseq one you should call merge_phyloseq() or the constructor phyloseq().
otumat <- t(read.table('otu.table.tsv',sep='\t',row.names=1,header=TRUE,quote=""))
OTU = otu_table(otumat, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)
mapmat <- read.table('mapping.tsv',sep='\t',row.names=1,header=TRUE)
MAP = sample_data(mapmat)
data = phyloseq(OTU, MAP)

phyloseq provides some objects to test the packages, that you could load with data():

library(phyloseq)
data(GlobalPatterns) # include environmental samples and some mock communities.

or as whatever R data, you could load() a phyloseq object previously saved in a file:

load('Ballou2016.Rdata') # chick gut samples, treated with probiotics and/or Salmonella vaccine

phyloseq Filter/Preprocess

phyloseq provides multiple functions to manipulate the microbiome data: filter|prune|subset_samples/taxa

  • Normalize: Get relative abundances from absolutes ones. Compute TSS (Total sum normalization per sample): abundance/sum of reads per sample
ballou2016.tss=transform_sample_counts(ballou2016, function(x) x / sum(x))

Clustering

Group data in different clusters is a very often machine learning technique applied in bioinformatics. How to do clustering, to evaluate (usually forgotten) and to interpretate their results with R?

Load a data table:

data=read.table('clusteringSampleData.csv',sep="\t",header=TRUE,row.names=1,check.names=FALSE)

Clustering evaluation

Check the performance of the clustering, for example, with Silhouette coefficient, measuring how good the samples are grouped. You can use the average silhouette width, i.e. a unique number averaging silhouette for all clusters and instances. It is a normalized measure between -1 and 1, where:
* Very strong clustering structure: >0.7 (within distance > between distance)
* Meaningful clustering structure: >0.25
* Bad clustering: <0 (instances misclassified)

library(cluster)
hc<-hclust(dist(data))
si<-silhouette(cutree(hc,k=4),dist(data))
plot(si)

summary(si)$avg.width
## [1] 0.3664977
for(i in 2:10){
  print(paste("k=",i,": ",summary(silhouette(cutree(hc,k=i),dist(data)))$avg.width,sep=''))
} # end-for

Clustering assignation

Save clusters assigned to each instance:

hc<-hclust(dist(data))
k=4
groups <- as.factor(cutree(hc,k=k))
write.table(groups,paste("hclust_clusters_k",k,".txt",sep=""),quote=FALSE,sep='\t',col.names=NA,row.names=TRUE)

Clusters coloured in scatterplot

With variables in diagonal:

library(car,quietly = TRUE)
##
